In medicine, the '''terminal drop hypothesis''' is a hypothesis that a sharp reduction in [[cognitive capacity]] in older people is often correlated with impending death, typically within five years.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1080/03610737508257957|pmid=802856|title=The terminal drop hypothesis: Fact or artifact?|journal=Experimental Aging Research|volume=1|issue=1|pages=169–85|year=2007|last1=Siegler|first1=Ilene C.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1093/geronj/43.6.P141|pmid=3183309|title=Is Terminal Drop Pervasive or Specific?|journal=Journal of Gerontology|volume=43|issue=6|pages=P141|year=1988|last1=White|first1=N.|last2=Cunningham|first2=W. R.}}</ref>

